```

Equivalent with raw Promises:

```js
function getUser(id) {
  return fetch(`/api/users/${id}`).then(res => res.json());
}
```

## Error handling

Use normal `try`/`catch` — rejections become thrown exceptions:

```js
async function load() {
  try {
    const user = await getUser(1);
  } catch (err) {
    console.error(err);
  }
}
```

## Common pitfall: sequential vs. parallel

`await` in a loop runs sequentially. To run in parallel, kick off the Promises first, then await:

```js
// Sequential — slow
for (const id of ids) {
  await getUser(id);
}

// Parallel — fast
const users = await Promise.all(ids.map(getUser));
```

## Key things to remember

- `await` only works inside `async` functions (or at the top level of ES modules).
- An `async` function never throws synchronously — errors come out as a rejected Promise.
- Forgetting `await` gives you a Promise instead of the value, often silently.

